question: the kinked demand curve in oligopoly is used to explain
response_text: In an oligopoly market, companies usually maintain stable prices and compete using methods other than price. The kinked demand curve model suggests that if one company increases prices, others will not follow suit to retain their market share. However, if one company decreases prices, others are likely to do the same to prevent losing customers. This leads to prices staying constant and competition focusing on advertising, product variations, and customer service.
